If the price of Ethereum goes down, your $100 can turn into $87, immediately #Aave sells your $87 and pay the lenders

But your $80 USDC still remains

Hope you get it?

For interest rates, there are algorithms to determine interest rates due to much liquidity (amount of money available for trading) in the pool

#AAVE is decentralized, hence the meaning of it's name (ghost)

Nobody sees what you're doing (no third parties) unlike Banks!

This is a smart contract that run automatically. Instead of P2P, #AAVE was peer - to - smart contract method

Lenders deposit money into smart contract and earn interest

Borrowers also deposit their collateral to another smart contract and borrow from any smart contract.

Two key problems they faced

âœ… Lack of liquidity (people were not ready to put up their money for borrowing)

âœ… Matching borrowers to lenders

In the example, the stable-rate provided by #Aave could have prevented the increase in borrow #APY, as it is designed to mitigate the impacts of market volatility on a loan. E.g. David has the option of a #DeFi loan with a variable interest rate and a stable-rate through #Aave. The variable interest rate is 6% and the stable interest rate is 7.79%.

Whereas #Compound offers exclusively variable-rates, #Aave provides both variable and stable-rate loans. The base interest for stable-rate loans will be inherently higher, in exchange for the added security and predictability.

Borrow #APY (annual percentage yield) refers to the interest rate borrowers pay to lenders, plus accrued interest and the time taken to repay. #Compound and #Aave, for instance, are two separate protocols with different lending options. https://t.co/5uufD5R0To
